  "text": "'Kin-founding', the founding of new populations by groups of relatives, is known to enhance the effects of population turnover, because kin-structuring reduces the effective population size of the founding groups [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Newly colonized populations of P. substriatus show a characteristic kin-structuring which can largely be attributed to the dispersal biology and mating patterns of the female beetles. Dispersal in P. substriatus is strongly female-biased and male beetles are rare in recently established populations . Consequently, most females will be inseminated in their native population, prior to dispersal. Moreover, dispersal distances are short, of the order of a few metres , resulting in only a few source populations being represented among the colonizing individuals. This increases the potential kin-structure even further because the different founding females may either be related or may share some of the mates in their native population.",
